snippet.textDisplay:
#Odisha   #Sambalpuri   #folkmusic  +  #Tamil   #Rap  -  #Awesome  fusion..
Keep going..  #SonaMohapatra  and  #Rituraj .. you guys have a quite appreciable job for the popularity of  #Odisha  and  #Odia   #Music  .. 
And for guys who came up with lots of criticism, let me ask a question, Did this happen earlier ever? They have tried something and the job is really commendable. You can post a positive comment off course. And this is a fusion or rendition kinda song.. have you ever heard hindi rap song where you have english and hindi mix raps.. Here it's in  #Tamil ..
And for guys who really worry for the original song.. Please listen it as many times as possible and dance, sing and do lots of masti.. Original is original and will be.. It's not killed neither will be.. It's still available.. It was an experiment to give a new fresh look and bit different than the original off course.. If you find it's same as the original, then why create this. It would be something like, Sona performs the song in Coke Studio..

snippet.textDisplay: Guys appreciate the effort , they have presented the song in a different form , but the major thing is it has reached to Non-Oriya audience. I sometimes do find remixes of Bengali original classics a bit outrageous but main thing is its reaching to non-Bengali audience as well. If you are a Bengali, or Oriya or Tamil preserve your own culture and heritage in your own space but also try to appreciate if someone gets influenced by your language and absorbs the essence in their own way. Try to appreciate the fact that the things you have a value is becoming popular with people who has not heard or seen it before. Language should unite us as a nation not divide us. Appreciate every language and culture , being Indian is a priviledge that we have so much rich treasures of language, culture and ethnic diversity. Appreciate and respect each and every one of them, don't impose your own on others, rather enrich and preserve what you have.

snippet.textDisplay:
Great job.....
Thanks  Sona Mohapatra  and Rituraj Mohanty for recreating these master pieces of Odia Music #Rangabati and #BandeUtkalaJanani.
It's time to show there is a state in India called Odisha which has its own and literature, culture and heritage.(To those people who say "where is Udisa"). In my opinion that tamil rap could have been avoided. 
Anyways a request: can you people recreate any song of Odia Music Maestro Akshaya Mohanty(the writer+ composer+singer). Who's neglected by today's Odia youth(who either don't understand the difficult words or driven by those noisy music with nonsense lyrics)
